</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Mold needs food, such as pollen and dirt, to survive. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d7/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d7/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Mold enjoys temperate weather, although mold spores can stay dormant through extreme weather situations, such as drought or frost. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Mold likes shady areas away from direct sun. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/11/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/11/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Build with a composite material that has mold inhibitors in its construction. Wood is very agreeable to mold spores, and decks built out of wood often suffer from mold problems. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Ultraviolet rays from sunlight will kill mold spores, so you may want to build a deck where there is adequate sunlight. You may also want to cut back as many trees around the deck area as possible. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7a/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7a/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slope the deck away from the house so that it drains well. Slope should be 1/8 inch (.32 cm) for every 8 feet (2.44 m) of deck. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Gap the decking material at least 1/8 inch (.32 cm) for adequate draining. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Mold-on-a-Deck-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
